Moroccan diplomacy appeared more dynamic when King Mohammed VI became the 20th century ruler, diplomats said.

New diplomatic feats were performed with Bahrain. Neither of the two countries had held a previous official meeting in their recent history, but very soon a joint committee between the two countries was established. It was the second after the one with Saudi Arabia and the UAE.

The three kingdoms formed the Association of Arab Maghreb States and they tried to make it work, but all attempts failed as Morocco insisted on its unity. Among the Arab countries, Morocco has diplomatic representation in the majority of the member countries of the Arab League.

It has pursued economic diplomacy with considerable success. Morocco, for instance, does not export phosphate to any company except one that is based in China. The flagship company of this mining is closely linked to the market price worldwide.

China deals with any country abroad on a state-to-state basis. It is a country that does not believe in the philosophy of world trade bodies. It is a country that prefers trade to be bilateral.

Morocco is not leaving behind China, which is the world’s largest consumer country. It is focusing on other important countries, and it wants to have more direct access to them.
